# Lore Engineering Standards

## Arrow Functions — Mandatory

All functions in `src/` MUST use arrow function syntax. `function` declarations are not allowed.

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT
export const buildApp = (deps: BuildAppDeps): FastifyInstance => { ... }
export const registerProject = async (db: DrizzleClient, input: Input): Promise<Output> => { ... }
const projectsController = (app: FastifyInstance, opts: Opts, done: DoneFn): void => { ... }
export default projectsController

// ❌ WRONG — never use these
export function buildApp(...) { ... }
export async function registerProject(...) { ... }
export default function projectsController(...) { ... }
```

## Layer Boundaries — Strict

The codebase uses a **Route → Controller → Service → Repository** four-layer architecture.

```
route → controller → service → repository
```

| Layer | Location | Responsibility | May Import | Must NOT Import |
|-------|----------|---------------|-----------|----------------|
| Route | `src/api/routes/` | Fastify plugin, URL, schema, preHandlers | Controllers | Services, Repositories, `drizzle-orm` |
| Controller | `src/api/controllers/` | Plain handler `(req, reply)`, response shaping | Services | Repositories, `drizzle-orm`, `pg` |
| Service | `src/services/` | Business logic, orchestration | Repositories | `fastify`, Fastify types |
| Repository | `src/repositories/` | Drizzle ORM queries only | `db/schema`, `db/client`, `drizzle-orm` | Services, Fastify |

```typescript
// ✅ Route — Fastify plugin wiring only
const projectsRoute = (app, opts, done) => {
  app.post('/register', { schema, preHandler: [requireAdminSecret] }, projectsController.register)
  done()
}

// ✅ Controller — plain handler, calls service
export const register = async (request, reply) => {
  const result = await projectsService.registerProject(request.body)
  reply.status(201)
  return result
}

// ✅ Service — business logic, calls repository
export const registerProject = async (input) => { ... }

// ✅ Repository — DB only
export const insertProject = async (db, data) => { /* drizzle query */ }

// ❌ WRONG — drizzle import in a route or controller
import { eq } from 'drizzle-orm'  // only allowed in repositories!

// ❌ WRONG — Fastify types in a service or repository
import { FastifyRequest } from 'fastify'  // only allowed in routes/controllers/middleware!
```

## File Naming

- Routes: `<resource>.route.ts` in `src/api/routes/`
- Controllers: `<resource>.controller.ts` in `src/api/controllers/` — export named handler functions
- Services: `<resource>.service.ts` in `src/services/`
- Repositories: `<resource>.repository.ts` in `src/repositories/`

## Tooling

- Package manager: **pnpm** only. Never run `npm install` or commit `package-lock.json`.
- Linter: `pnpm lint` (oxlint)
- Formatter: `pnpm format` (prettier)
- All new code must pass `pnpm lint` and `pnpm format:check` before commit.

## Dependency Versions — Always Current Major

**Always use the current version available on npm, pinned with `^` (caret) so minor and patch updates are picked up automatically.** Never install an old major version unless a documented breaking-change reason exists in this file.

```bash
# ✅ CORRECT — check npm for the current version, then install with ^
# e.g. openai is at 6.37.0 on npm → install ^6.37.0
pnpm add openai@latest        # resolves to current version automatically
pnpm add drizzle-orm@latest
pnpm add fastify@latest

# ❌ WRONG — pinning to an old major without a documented reason
pnpm add openai@^4
pnpm add some-package@2.x
```

- "Latest" means whatever the current major version is on npm right now (e.g. `^6.x` for openai, not `^4.x`).
- When a story spec or planning artifact names an older version (e.g. `^4.x`), **ignore it** and install the current npm version instead.
- If upgrading to the current major introduces a real breaking change that cannot be resolved immediately, document it here with a dated comment before pinning an older version.
- Run `pnpm outdated` periodically and update packages proactively.

## Request Validation — Fastify Schema, Not Manual Guards

All `POST`/`PUT`/`PATCH` routes **MUST** declare a `schema: { body: ... }` JSON Schema in the route options. Controllers must **NOT** contain manual type-checking or presence guards (`if (!field)`, `typeof field !== "string"`, etc.).

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT — schema on the route, clean controller
// src/api/routes/mcp.route.ts
const myToolBodySchema = {
  type: "object",
  required: ["title", "value"],
  properties: {
    title: { type: "string", minLength: 1 },
    value: { type: "number" },
    tag:   { type: "string", default: "general" }, // Ajv fills in defaults
  },
};

app.post("/tools/my_tool", {
  preHandler: [requireProjectAuth],
  schema: { body: myToolBodySchema },
}, handler);

// src/api/controllers/my-tool.controller.ts
export const myToolHandler = async (request: FastifyRequest, reply: FastifyReply) => {
  const { title, value, tag } = request.body as MyToolBody; // already validated
  // ... call service directly, no guards needed
};

// ❌ WRONG — manual validation in the controller
export const myToolHandler = async (request, reply) => {
  const body = request.body as any;
  if (!body.title || typeof body.title !== "string") {  // ← never do this
    throw validationError("title is required");
  }
};
```

- Fastify's built-in Ajv validates the body **before** `preHandler` runs, returning `400` automatically.
- The `setErrorHandler` in `src/api/app.ts` normalises Ajv errors into `{ error: "validation_error" }`.
- Use `default:` in the schema for optional fields with fallback values (`severity: { ..., default: "medium" }`); Ajv injects them so the controller always receives a fully-typed body.
- Inline schemas in the route file are preferred while there are ≤ 5 tools. Extract to `src/api/schemas/mcp.schemas.ts` only when schemas grow large or are shared across routes.
